@@eThe Arroyo -- As Kowloon Sees It@@N

@@WTemple Circle and Harbor Syndics, Joint Assessment@@N

The Arroyo is a dry canyon carved by a river that no longer flows,
and everything about it makes Kowloon recoil in recognition. @@yWater
volume translated into legal obligation.@@N Debts written against
drought. Oaths notarized against thirst. The Harbor Syndics see
@@rour own worst tendencies taken to their terminal point@@N.

Kowloon is @@ywater-conscious@@N. The Jhen River and Coppersalt Bay
define us. Our @@lsluice codes@@N regulate flow. During the @@rAshfall
Monsoon@@N, water allocation was life-and-death authority. We know
how close that comes to the Arroyo's @@ythirst oaths@@N: declarations
binding survival to institutional permission. The difference: Kowloon
@@ysunset its rationing authority@@N. The Arroyo's institutions never did.

Five layers remain active simultaneously. @@yKeeper-era@@N measurement
-- thirst oaths, witness stones recording water debt -- parallels
our @@eCourier Lantern Office@@N census. @@ySalt Ledger@@N extraction --
toll courts and mortuary intake for those who died in arrears --
parallels our @@lharbor tariff@@N pushed past all moral limit.
@@dPyramid jurisdiction@@N reframing debt as spiritual trespass parallels
nothing in Kowloon, and we are grateful.

The @@rSynod coercion@@N layer -- "authorized thirst" as both prayer
and threat -- is what the Temple Circle calls @@rthe weaponization of
need@@N. Water, like funerary rites, is @@ynon-negotiable provision@@N.
You do not withhold water to collect debt. You do not withhold naming
to collect fees. The Arroyo did both.

The @@d"unpaid names"@@N haunt the Temple Circle most -- dead whose rites
were withheld pending debt settlement, souls in administrative
suspension. In Kowloon, the @@dAshfall Registry@@N exists because six
hundred drowned in Yen-Mak and the survivors swore @@yevery death
would be named@@N. The unpaid names are a @@rviolation of the most basic
compact between living and dead@@N.

The @@dDustbound Court-Dead@@N -- raised assessors still demanding
declarations -- are registry without registrar. The Courier Lantern
Office classifies these as @@rsignal echoes@@N: institutional patterns
repeating after the institution has died. Canyon walls carry
overwritten inscriptions. The Jade Magistracy calls this @@ypalimpsest
governance@@N. Kowloon's terraced stone carries the same layers -- but
we @@yread@@N ours.

The Arroyo's water-debt system is @@yhorrifyingly familiar@@N: our own
harbor licensing stripped of mercy, accountability, and sunset. The
Arroyo is not a foreign horror. It is a @@rlocal possibility@@N --
the version of Kowloon that forgot why the lanterns were lit.
